{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656588"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18753"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62838"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10427"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26585"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the retina, photoreceptors form specialised synaptic connections with bipolar cells to transmit visual information. These synapses must maintain continuous neurotransmitter release in darkness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes neurotransmitter release from retinal photoreceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continuous GABA release in light","Pulsatile dopamine release in darkness","Increased acetylcholine release in light","Increased glycine release in darkness","Continuous glutamate release in darkness"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinuous glutamate release in darkness\u003C/strong\u003E. Photoreceptors contain ribbon synapses that enable sustained release of glutamate in darkness through specialized calcium channels. When light strikes the photoreceptor, it hyperpolarises the cell membrane, reducing glutamate release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased acetylcholine release in light\u003C/strong\u003E - Acetylcholine is not a major neurotransmitter in the retinal photoreceptor pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulsatile dopamine release in darkness\u003C/strong\u003E - Dopamine is released by amacrine cells, not photoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous GABA release in light\u003C/strong\u003E - GABA is released by horizontal and amacrine cells, not photoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glycine release in darkness\u003C/strong\u003E - Glycine is released by specific amacrine cells, not photoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis continuous release of glutamate in darkness is essential for normal visual processing, as it allows photoreceptors to signal both increases and decreases in light intensity through modulation of their release rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glutamate is the primary excitatory neurotransmitter released by photoreceptors in the retina.","Photoreceptors continuously release glutamate in darkness and decrease release when stimulated by light.","Ribbon synapses in photoreceptors enable sustained neurotransmitter release through specialized calcium channels."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T16:28:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T16:29:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10